Fidelity® Select Pharmaceuticals Portfolio


Symbol: FPHAX




									
										
											No Transaction Fee 1













           		Add to Watch List





				Compare


















































		 			Portfolio Manager Q&A
		 		

Chairman's Message


Investment Approach




Fidelity® Select Pharmaceuticals Portfolio: Portfolio Manager Q&A

FEBRUARY 28, 2017
View as PDF


Fund Managers
Asher Anolic

Key Takeaways



For the fiscal year ending February 28, 2017, the fund gained 0.57%, lagging the 4.53% result of the S&P® Custom Pharmaceuticals Index.

Pharmaceuticals stocks underperformed the broad-market S&P 500® by a considerable margin the past 12 months, as concerns about drug pricing reached a fever pitch.

Relative to the industry benchmark, a sizable out-of-index stake in Teva Pharmaceutical Industries was the fund's biggest individual detractor.

Conversely, avoiding Canada-based Concordia International, an index component, aided relative results. 

Portfolio Manager Asher Anolic believes pricing concerns and merger-and-acquisition activity will persist. He looks to upcoming innovations in oncology, cardiology and neurology to drive industry valuations.



Q&A


An interview with Portfolio Manager Asher Anolic

How did the fund and industry perform for the fiscal year ending February 28, 2017?
The fund gained 0.57%, lagging the 4.53% result of the S&P® Custom Pharmaceuticals Index. Both the fund and the S&P industry index considerably underperformed the 24.98% result of the broad-market S&P 500. The fund significantly trailed its peer group average, which is tied to the broader health care sector.
Concerns about drug pricing reached a fever pitch the past year, resulting in the industry's significant underperformance of the broad market. Driving the dialogue was a series of news articles criticizing pricing practices by specialty pharmaceutical companies, as well as heightened focus on the subject leading up to the November U.S. presidential election. While one might have thought Donald Trump's election and his anti-regulation stance would restore confidence to the industry, the President shattered that hope in January when he told Time magazine he wanted to lower drug prices.

Why did the fund underperform the S&P industry index the past 12 months?
In our most recent performance review, I discussed three broad themes that worked against us for the six months ending August 31. Unfortunately, these factors continued to weigh on the fund's relative performance, leading to disappointing results for the fiscal year ending February 28.
First, the fund was poorly positioned among specialty pharma firms with falling earnings estimates. These companies appeared to have low expectations coming into the first quarter of 2017. However, expectations were not low enough in the face of a jittery market. As a result, many firms that either missed or reported earnings in line with estimates were punished – often unfairly, in my view.
Included in this bucket was a sizable out-of-index stake in Teva Pharmaceutical Industries, the fund's biggest individual detractor. Our stake returned roughly -36%, as Teva's stock price and the firm's financial results were hampered by significant concern about the pricing environment for generic drugs and the durability of the firm's key multiple sclerosis drug, Copaxone®. In addition, investors thought that Teva had overpaid to acquire the Actavis Generics business from Allergan. As pressure continued to mount on Teva and its shares, I decided to significantly reduce our stake.
Another drawback for the fund was that investors favored stocks of more-defensive companies offering high dividend yields, particularly early in the period, even if these firms lacked improving underlying fundamentals. This hurt the fund because I prefer to hold companies with good asset duration, rather than focusing purely on dividend yield.
An underweighting in pharma giant Merck, another big relative detractor, largely fit this description. The stock had lagged the index for several years. However, it rose about 35% the past year, as one of the firm's cancer drugs showed a particularly strong benefit in patients with metastatic non-small-cell lung cancer, while a competitor's drug did not. Based on the firm's improved competitive position, I increased the fund's allocation to Merck the past 12 months, but remained underweighted at period end.

What was the third broad theme?
The U.S. government began to crack down on tax inversions, which held back merger-and-acquisition (M&A) activity among some large-cap pharma firms, including some held in the fund. In addition, I largely avoided small-cap firms that were either acquired or in talks to be acquired for hefty premiums because I saw too much risk.
Ireland-based Allergan was representative of these challenges. Allergan was among the fund's largest holdings, and I was hopeful that the company's planned merger with Pfizer would close. Unfortunately, the companies called off the deal in April, after the U.S. Treasury announced new regulations aimed at curbing tax inversions, and Allergan's stock sold off.

Where did you find success?
I decided to avoid Canada-based Concordia International and underweight Perrigo during the first half of the period. This helped, as shares of Perrigo and Concordia meaningfully declined. Generics maker Perrigo and Concordia – which makes drugs to treat attention-deficit hyperactivity disorder (ADHD), cancer and asthma – had rapidly grown earnings prior to this reporting period, due in part to the firms' aggressive acquisition strategies. I believed price competition for their key products would hurt the earnings of both firms. With Perrigo, however, I added to our position amid change in senior leadership at the company and recognition that generic woes were mostly priced into the stock. I also believed the rest of the operational business was consumer focused and should be steadier over the long term.
With Novo-Nordisk, I was concerned about the long-term pricing environment for diabetes drugmakers, so I underweighted the stock and continued to reduce the fund's position the past year. The company cut its full-year profit estimate, and the stock was hampered further in October by falling insulin prices. Overall, our holdings returned roughly -30% for the period.

Asher, what is your outlook?I believe that the Trump administration likely will blunt the push for legislation to regulate drug pricing. Yet, concern about pricing will still loom in the background.
The industry's overcapacity, combined with cheaper, still-effective therapies and a motivated intermediary in the form of pharmacy benefit managers (PBMs), should limit pricing in an expanding number of therapeutic areas. Therefore, I believe the traditional business model embraced by specialty pharma companies – where firms borrow to purchase assets with the aim of increasing price to show strong returns – is likely obsolete. Similarly, major pharma firms that relied on price increases to offset volume declines on a large granular tail of aging products may find it difficult to keep up the pace at which they've been operating in recent years.
Large-cap therapeutics companies with sizable revenue bases tend to have trouble sustaining an active internal pipeline of new drugs and could struggle to create consistent, organic growth. However, a potential assist from the government in the form of corporate tax reform could spark large scale M&A activity. These deals tend to result in poor performance of the acquiring entity until synergies are realized, so I've reduced exposure to companies likely to be acquirers. ■
_______________________________________________
Note to shareholders: On April 1, 2017, the fund's industry benchmark will change from the S&P® Custom Pharmaceuticals Index to the MSCI North America IMI + ADR Custom Pharmaceuticals 25/50 Linked Index. Due to new international benchmark guidelines, S&P® Dow Jones® Indices has decided to stop offering its brand on custom benchmarks, effective March 31, 2017. Fidelity believes that the new MSCI index will continue to provide shareholders with meaningful performance comparisons. 





Asher Anolic on upcoming innovation in pharma:


"I believe the most exciting innovative events will be isolated one-offs and launches of drugs where we've already seen the data sets. In oncology, usage of the class of drugs known as immunotherapies continued to expand the past year, including new tumor types and earlier lines of therapy. Drugs currently on the market for a variety of cancer types tend to work in anywhere between one-fifth and one-third of the addressable population. Thus, for the next level of acceptance, combinations with other therapies must demonstrate extended survival for a wider swath of the population. In this vein, 2017 looks rather bare to me, as key trials in combination with chemotherapy will come to light. But the more potentially paradigm-shifting events are likely to occur in 2018 and beyond.
"Elsewhere in oncology, a key treatment for multiple myeloma made inroads into the first-line metastatic setting, and we are starting to see the emergence of a class of drug that repairs damage to DNA and helps prevent the spread of cancer.
"Turning to cardiology, 2017 should bring additional data in large patient populations for a new class of lipid-lowering drug that shows a benefit in adverse cardiac events. These drugs have been approved, but sales to date have been modest because insurers have been able to block uptake until more data arrives.
"In neurology, Merck's newest pill to treat Alzheimer's disease is expected to show trial results around mid-2017.
"Overall, promising pipeline drugs from pharma companies should support valuation levels and could lead to revaluation, in my view. Among innovators, the fund has greater exposure to companies whose key innovative products dovetail with a relatively low pipeline valuation."




MARKET RECAP


The U.S. equity bellwether S&P 500® index gained 24.98% for the year ending February 28, 2017, rising sharply in the period's final four months on renewed optimism for economic growth. The beginning of the period saw improving investor sentiment amid U.S. job gains, a rally in energy and other stimuli that helped keep the seven-year bull uptrend intact. Markets tumbled briefly following Brexit – the U.K.'s June vote to exit the European Union –recovering quickly to settle into a flattish stretch until the November U.S. presidential election. Stocks then broke out in response to Donald Trump's surprise victory, surging to a series of new all-time highs on expectations for reflation and fiscal stimulus. For the year, financials (+47%) proved the top-performing sector by far, riding an uptick in bond yields and a rally in banks, especially post-election. Industrials (+27%), energy (+26%) and materials (+28%) also fared well, the latter two driven by a cyclical rebound in commodity prices. Information technology rose 33%, despite cooling off late in 2016. Conversely, real estate and health care each returned 15%, lagging the broad market on prospects of rising interest rates and an uncertain political and regulatory outlook, respectively. An improved backdrop for riskier assets curbed dividend-rich telecom services (+9%), consumer staples (+12%) and utilities (+16%).



